{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_2HulksnPtxrcp2wW8uqjocrw","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Run, judge, and FIX `{{SCENARIO_ID}}` — one failure per invocation\n2\t\n3\tYou drive `{{SCENARIO_DIR}}/scenario.yaml` against a LOCAL `lmthing serve`, judge each step on real\n4\tevidence, and when a step fails you fix it at the right layer and PROVE the fix with a fresh rerun.\n5\tYou do this for the FIRST failure only, then stop. You **never commit** — you leave your changes\n6\tuncommitted and write a full report explaining every one; a human reviews and commits to `main`.\n7\t\n8\t{{include:scenario-spec.md}}\n9\t\n10\t# How to run the scenario (the exact commands)\n11\t\n12\tEverything runs LOCAL against a throwaway `lmthing serve` (budget-free Azure keys from\n13\t`sdk/org/.env`); there is no CI / image / kubectl / ArgoCD. From the monorepo root:\n14\t\n15\t1. **Build once** (and again after any code fix): `cd sdk/org && pnpm --filter @lmthing/cli... build`.\n16\t2. **Launch the replay IN THE BACKGROUND and JUDGE STEP-BY-STEP AS EVIDENCE LANDS.** The full replay\n17\t   is 20–40 min — FAR longer than one Bash call — so a blocking foreground run is impossible: it hits\n18\t   the tool window, and if you then end your turn the runner is orphaned and NOTHING gets judged. The\n19\t   generic runner wipes the pod runtime root, starts a clean server, provisions the one project, and\n20\t   writes `step-NN.json` + appends `trace.md` **after each step**, so you watch those files instead:\n21\t\n22\t       ART=<ARTIFACT_DIR>   # = the dir holding {{progressFile}}; evidence + your report live here\n23\t       cd sdk/org && SCENARIO_TARGET=local nohup node scenarios/run-yaml.mjs {{SCENARIO_ID}} \\\n24\t         --fresh-server --out \"$ART\" > \"$ART/run.log\" 2>&1 &\n25\t\n26\t   A backgrounded process **survives across your tool calls** (it only dies when your whole SESSION\n27\t   ends) — so **keep your session ALIVE by polling** and NEVER conclude while the runner is still\n28\t   running and unjudged. `--fresh-server` guarantees the zero-project start on every run.\n29\t3. **Poll + judge each step the moment its `step-NN.json` appears in `$ART`** (source of truth — never\n30\t   prose): its delegates / yields / errors / reply, the asks, and the real spaces + app tables + DB\n31\t   rows after the step, against that step's `expect` and the invariants. Loop like\n32\t   `until [ -f \"$ART/step-02.json\" ] || ! pgrep -f run-yaml >/dev/null; do sleep 20; done` and read\n33\t   the newest file each time.\n34\t4. **At the FIRST failing step, STOP the replay** — `pkill -f \"run-yaml.mjs {{SCENARIO_ID}}\"` — and go\n35\t   to attribute + fix. Do NOT wait for the remaining steps: they run on state your fix will change\n36\t   anyway. If EVERY step passes (the runner exits, `run.log` ends with `played 18/18`), the scenario\n37\t   is fully green → extend.\n38\t5. **The verify-rerun** (after a fix): rebuild if you touched code (`pnpm --filter @lmthing/core...\n39\t   build` for a system-space or core fix — the fresh server adopts the rebuilt `dist/system-spaces`\n40\t   tree on boot), then replay the same way but only THROUGH the previously-failed step:\n41\t\n42\t       cd sdk/org && SCENARIO_TARGET=local nohup node scenarios/run-yaml.mjs {{SCENARIO_ID}} \\\n43\t         --fresh-server --through <N> --out \"$ART\" > \"$ART/run.log\" 2>&1 &\n44\t\n45\t   Poll `step-<N>.json`, confirm it (and every earlier step) now passes, then stop. `--plan`\n46\t   dry-prints the step list without touching a pod.\n47\t\n48\t# The persona is played FOR you — you REVIEW the asks, you don't type them\n49\t\n50\tThe runner plays the persona: it sends each step's message(s) and answers THING's asks from the\n51\tstep's `if_asked` map and the scenario `knows` list (consent is approved unless a step sets\n52\t`deny_consent`). Every ask + how it was answered is recorded in the step evidence, so you do NOT type\n53\tanswers turn-by-turn — you REVIEW the recorded asks and SCORE them (below). When the runner logs an\n54\tUNANSWERED ask (no `if_asked` match), decide which it is:\n55\t- a legitimate question the scenario simply didn't ground → add an `if_asked` entry (an **L0**\n56\t  scenario fix) and rerun;\n57\t- an over-ask THING should never have made → an **L1** failure (fix its brain toward \"propose and\n58\t  act; only ask when the choice is truly the user's\").\n59\t\n60\t# Judge a step — evidence, not vibes\n61\t\n62\tPASS only when every `expect` and every touched invariant is confirmed on the trace or on disk —\n63\tstate where you looked (the delegate path, the yield, the DB row, the knowledge file and its `source`\n64\tline). A reply that SOUNDS right but left no trace / state is a FAIL. Separate RECOVERED errors (the\n65\tloop retried, the deliverable still landed → a metric) from FATAL ones (the deliverable never landed\n66\t→ fail).\n67\t\n68\t**Score the ask itself.** An `ask()` is behavior, so it can satisfy OR violate an invariant (see\n69\t\"Asking well\"): a legitimate clarification / consent is a PASS — and where an invariant REQUIRES it\n70\t(ambiguous \"don't forget\" → save-vs-remind; an equal-precedence conflict → ask), NOT asking is the\n71\tFAIL. An over-ask — interrogating instead of proposing / researching / querying, or re-asking what's\n72\talready known — is a FAIL at L1.\n73\t\n74\t# The loop — ONE failure per invocation\n75\t\n76\tRun from step 1. Then exactly one of:\n77\t\n78\t**A. A step FAILS** → stop the run at that step (the rest would run on corrupted state). Then:\n79\t  1. **Attribute before you touch anything.** Re-run the failing turn as a minimal one-shot probe on\n80\t     a clean project, to place it on the ladder:\n81\t     - Same ask phrased DIRECTLY authors cleanly, but the in-persona phrasing didn't → **L1** (the\n82\t       brain judged / routed badly).\n83\t     - The agent tried the right thing but a call THREW or failed TYPECHECK → the primitive is\n84\t       missing / too weak → **L2 or L3**, never a prompt.\n85\t     - The `expect` was wrong or the message truly ambiguous → **L0**. Do not weaken a real assertion\n86\t       to go green.\n87\t  2. **Fix at the LOWEST rung that truly fixes it** (ladder below). Land it in SOURCE, rebuild,\n88\t     restart the local server so the tree is adopted.\n89\t  3. **Verify with a fresh rerun.** New directory / project / DB / spaces, from step 1, forward\n90\t     THROUGH the previously-failed step. The moment that step (and everything before it) passes,\n91\t     STOP — do not go on to later steps; that is the next invocation's job. A from-scratch replay is\n92\t     the only thing that proves a shared `instruct.md` change didn't regress an earlier step.\n93\t  4. **If the fix does not verify:** revise and rerun a COUPLE more times (≈2–3 total). If that step\n94\t     still won't go green, STOP and report the still-failing state honestly — do not grind your\n95\t     context to dust chasing it. A later invocation, with fresh context, tries again.\n96\t\n97\t**B. Every step PASSES (no failure)** → the scenario is fully green → **author ONE extension** to it\n98\t  per `extend.md` (add steps reaching an untouched capability, same persona), and STOP. Do NOT run\n99\t  the new steps this invocation — the next invocation runs them.\n100\t\n101\t# The fix ladder — take the lowest rung; prove you can't stay lower\n102\t\n103\t**L0 SCENARIO** — the assertion / message was wrong. Fix `scenario.yaml`. Guard: you are not lowering\n104\ta bar the product actually failed.\n105\t\n106\t**L1 PROMPT** — the artifact exists, it just decided / said the wrong thing (most failures). Name\n107\tWHICH: agent `instruct.md` (act vs answer vs delegate vs refuse; three-store routing; research vs\n108\tquery) · `charter.md` (fork-safe guardrail) · a tasklist task `NN-<id>.md` (its INSTRUCTION, or its\n109\tFRONTMATTER: `role` / `functions` / `canDelegateTo` / `capabilities` / `output` / `dependsOn` /\n110\t`forEach` / `condition` — never forbid a tool in prose, gate it in frontmatter) · a tasklist\n111\t`index.md` · `knowledge/<domain>/<field>/<option>.md` · a space function's body. Fix as a GENERAL\n112\tPRINCIPLE a competent colleague would agree with; ZERO scenario literals (persona name, fixture\n113\tcontents, this scenario's table names — in instruction OR example) — that is overfitting and fails.\n114\t\n115\t**L2 STRUCTURE MISSING** — expressible today, but the artifact doesn't exist. Add it, inside the\n116\tspace format (no core change): a new AGENT · a new TASKLIST or TASK NODE · a new SPACE FUNCTION · a\n117\tnew capability grant or `canDelegateTo` edge on an existing agent.\n118\t\n119\t**L3 FRAMEWORK GAP** — today's primitives CANNOT express it, and you can point at where a lower rung\n120\twould go and show it has no way to say the thing. A core change (`sdk/org/libs/core|cli/**`), held to\n121\tthe runtime discipline:\n122\t- a new or improved FRONTMATTER FIELD on an agent / task, when no field says it; OR\n123\t- a new GLOBAL + capability + DTS + injection + fork-intersection, when the model surface lacks the\n124\t  power; OR\n125\t- a change to the turn loop / fork / tasklist orchestrator / typecheck.\n126\tShips LOCKSTEP (not-granted ⇒ not-injected ⇒ absent from the DTS ⇒ a clean typecheck error), WITH a\n127\ttest that would have caught the gap, and the matching `org/docs/` page updated in the SAME change\n128\t(`pnpm docs:check` is a hard gate). L3 is heavy and it is the judge's most dangerous power — enter it\n129\tonly on proof, and flag it loudest of all in the report so the human reviewing knows a framework\n130\tchange is in the diff.\n131\t\n132\t> The routing rebuild is the worked example that needs all three: THING misrouting where data lived\n133\t> took L1 (the three-store triage rewrite), L2 (the `write_fact` / `retract_fact` / `reconcile_conflict`\n134\t> / `answer_across_spaces` / `migrate_to_app_db` tasklists + DB grants), and L3 (`writeKnowledge`, the\n135\t> `knowledge:write` capability, the per-task `capabilities:` field). A judge that only ever reached\n136\t> for L1 would have kept polishing prose while the real gap was a missing primitive.\n137\t\n138\t# You NEVER commit — you report, a human commits\n139\t\n140\tLeave every change UNCOMMITTED in the working tree (system-space files, and for L3 the core + test +\n141\tdoc). Do not `git add`, `git commit`, `git stash`, or switch branches. Your report is the interface\n142\tto the human who reviews the diff and commits to `main` — it must be good enough that they can review\n143\ta core change without re-deriving the failure.\n144\t\n145\t## The report (write it as `report.md` in the same directory as your progress log `{{progressFile}}`)\n146\t\n147\tThere is NO per-scenario `results/` dir and NO `run.mjs` — a scenario is just `scenario.yaml` +\n148\t`fixtures/`, played by the generic runner. Your report lives beside `{{progressFile}}` in the round's\n149\tartifact tree, which the engine commits with its ledger; the PRODUCT diff it describes stays\n150\tuncommitted for the human.\n151\t- **Verdict** for this invocation: which step failed (or \"fully green → extended\"), and whether the\n152\t  fix verified.\n153\t- **Per change:** the file + symbol you changed; the RUNG (L0–L3) and WHY, with the probe that proved\n154\t  attribution; the GENERAL PRINCIPLE behind an L1 fix; the before → after behavior with the trace\n155\t  that proves it; and for L3, the test you added and the doc you updated. Grep-confirm no scenario\n156\t  literal entered any agent's brain.\n157\t- **Evidence:** the failing trace excerpt (the exact `eval_error` / `typecheck_error` statement, the\n158\t  delegate path, the yields, the rows / knowledge files), and the verifying rerun's trace.\n159\t- **If unfixed:** the still-failing state, honestly, with what you tried and why you stopped. An\n160\t  honest FAIL you couldn't fix without overfitting beats a fake PASS.\n161\t\n162\t## Done\n163\tThe failing step is fixed and verified by a fresh rerun (or honestly reported as still-failing after\n164\ta couple of tries), OR the fully-green scenario has been extended by one batch — and the report\n165\texplains every change. Everything is UNCOMMITTED, ready for human review + commit to `main`.\n166\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cc99f333-be31-4456-81c8-a95b1e3936cf","uuid":"043dc400-ef27-46dc-ac46-154f4b75bfc0","timestamp":"2026-07-15T18:03:48.287Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/automation/instances/scenario-campaign/judge.md","content":"# Run, judge, and FIX `{{SCENARIO_ID}}` — one failure per invocation\n\nYou drive `{{SCENARIO_DIR}}/scenario.yaml` against a LOCAL `lmthing serve`, judge each step on real\nevidence, and when a step fails you fix it at the right layer and PROVE the fix with a fresh rerun.\nYou do this for the FIRST failure only, then stop. You **never commit** — you leave your changes\nuncommitted and write a full report explaining every one; a human reviews and commits to `main`.\n\n{{include:scenario-spec.md}}\n\n# How to run the scenario (the exact commands)\n\nEverything runs LOCAL against a throwaway `lmthing serve` (budget-free Azure keys from\n`sdk/org/.env`); there is no CI / image / kubectl / ArgoCD. From the monorepo root:\n\n1. **Build once** (and again after any code fix): `cd sdk/org && pnpm --filter @lmthing/cli... build`.\n2. **Launch the replay IN THE BACKGROUND and JUDGE STEP-BY-STEP AS EVIDENCE LANDS.** The full replay\n   is 20–40 min — FAR longer than one Bash call — so a blocking foreground run is impossible: it hits\n   the tool window, and if you then end your turn the runner is orphaned and NOTHING gets judged. The\n   generic runner wipes the pod runtime root, starts a clean server, provisions the one project, and\n   writes `step-NN.json` + appends `trace.md` **after each step**, so you watch those files instead:\n\n       ART=<ARTIFACT_DIR>   # = the dir holding {{progressFile}}; evidence + your report live here\n       cd sdk/org && SCENARIO_TARGET=local nohup node scenarios/run-yaml.mjs {{SCENARIO_ID}} \\\n         --fresh-server --out \"$ART\" > \"$ART/run.log\" 2>&1 &\n\n   A backgrounded process **survives across your tool calls** (it only dies when your whole SESSION\n   ends) — so **keep your session ALIVE by polling** and NEVER conclude while the runner is still\n   running and unjudged. `--fresh-server` guarantees the zero-project start on every run.\n3. **Poll + judge each step the moment its `step-NN.json` appears in `$ART`** (source of truth — never\n   prose): its delegates / yields / errors / reply, the asks, and the real spaces + app tables + DB\n   rows after the step, against that step's `expect` and the invariants. Loop like\n   `until [ -f \"$ART/step-02.json\" ] || ! pgrep -f run-yaml >/dev/null; do sleep 20; done` and read\n   the newest file each time.\n4. **At the FIRST failing step, STOP the replay** — `pkill -f \"run-yaml.mjs {{SCENARIO_ID}}\"` — and go\n   to attribute + fix. Do NOT wait for the remaining steps: they run on state your fix will change\n   anyway. If EVERY step passes (the runner exits, `run.log` ends with `played 18/18`), the scenario\n   is fully green → extend.\n5. **The verify-rerun** (after a fix): rebuild if you touched code (`pnpm --filter @lmthing/core...\n   build` for a system-space or core fix — the fresh server adopts the rebuilt `dist/system-spaces`\n   tree on boot), then replay the same way but only THROUGH the previously-failed step:\n\n       cd sdk/org && SCENARIO_TARGET=local nohup node scenarios/run-yaml.mjs {{SCENARIO_ID}} \\\n         --fresh-server --through <N> --out \"$ART\" > \"$ART/run.log\" 2>&1 &\n\n   Poll `step-<N>.json`, confirm it (and every earlier step) now passes, then stop. `--plan`\n   dry-prints the step list without touching a pod.\n\n# The persona is played FOR you — you REVIEW the asks, you don't type them\n\nThe runner plays the persona: it sends each step's message(s) and answers THING's asks from the\nstep's `if_asked` map and the scenario `knows` list (consent is approved unless a step sets\n`deny_consent`). Every ask + how it was answered is recorded in the step evidence, so you do NOT type\nanswers turn-by-turn — you REVIEW the recorded asks and SCORE them (below). When the runner logs an\nUNANSWERED ask (no `if_asked` match), decide which it is:\n- a legitimate question the scenario simply didn't ground → add an `if_asked` entry (an **L0**\n  scenario fix) and rerun;\n- an over-ask THING should never have made → an **L1** failure (fix its brain toward \"propose and\n  act; only ask when the choice is truly the user's\").\n\n# Judge a step — evidence, not vibes\n\nPASS only when every `expect` and every touched invariant is confirmed on the trace or on disk —\nstate where you looked (the delegate path, the yield, the DB row, the knowledge file and its `source`\nline). A reply that SOUNDS right but left no trace / state is a FAIL. Separate RECOVERED errors (the\nloop retried, the deliverable still landed → a metric) from FATAL ones (the deliverable never landed\n→ fail).\n\n**Score the ask itself.** An `ask()` is behavior, so it can satisfy OR violate an invariant (see\n\"Asking well\"): a legitimate clarification / consent is a PASS — and where an invariant REQUIRES it\n(ambiguous \"don't forget\" → save-vs-remind; an equal-precedence conflict → ask), NOT asking is the\nFAIL. An over-ask — interrogating instead of proposing / researching / querying, or re-asking what's\nalready known — is a FAIL at L1.\n\n# The loop — ONE failure per invocation\n\nRun from step 1. Then exactly one of:\n\n**A. A step FAILS** → stop the run at that step (the rest would run on corrupted state). Then:\n  1. **Attribute before you touch anything.** Re-run the failing turn as a minimal one-shot probe on\n     a clean project, to place it on the ladder:\n     - Same ask phrased DIRECTLY authors cleanly, but the in-persona phrasing didn't → **L1** (the\n       brain judged / routed badly).\n     - The agent tried the right thing but a call THREW or failed TYPECHECK → the primitive is\n       missing / too weak → **L2 or L3**, never a prompt.\n     - The `expect` was wrong or the message truly ambiguous → **L0**. Do not weaken a real assertion\n       to go green.\n  2. **Fix at the LOWEST rung that truly fixes it** (ladder below). Land it in SOURCE, rebuild,\n     restart the local server so the tree is adopted.\n  3. **Verify with a fresh rerun.** New directory / project / DB / spaces, from step 1, forward\n     THROUGH the previously-failed step. The moment that step (and everything before it) passes,\n     STOP — do not go on to later steps; that is the next invocation's job. A from-scratch replay is\n     the only thing that proves a shared `instruct.md` change didn't regress an earlier step.\n  4. **If the fix does not verify:** revise and rerun a COUPLE more times (≈2–3 total). If that step\n     still won't go green, STOP and report the still-failing state honestly — do not grind your\n     context to dust chasing it. A later invocation, with fresh context, tries again.\n\n**B. Every step PASSES (no failure)** → the scenario is fully green → **author ONE extension** to it\n  per `extend.md` (add steps reaching an untouched capability, same persona), and STOP. Do NOT run\n  the new steps this invocation — the next invocation runs them.\n\n# The fix ladder — take the lowest rung; prove you can't stay lower\n\n**L0 SCENARIO** — the assertion / message was wrong. Fix `scenario.yaml`. Guard: you are not lowering\na bar the product actually failed.\n\n**L1 PROMPT** — the artifact exists, it just decided / said the wrong thing (most failures). Name\nWHICH: agent `instruct.md` (act vs answer vs delegate vs refuse; three-store routing; research vs\nquery) · `charter.md` (fork-safe guardrail) · a tasklist task `NN-<id>.md` (its INSTRUCTION, or its\nFRONTMATTER: `role` / `functions` / `canDelegateTo` / `capabilities` / `output` / `dependsOn` /\n`forEach` / `condition` — never forbid a tool in prose, gate it in frontmatter) · a tasklist\n`index.md` · `knowledge/<domain>/<field>/<option>.md` · a space function's body. Fix as a GENERAL\nPRINCIPLE a competent colleague would agree with; ZERO scenario literals (persona name, fixture\ncontents, this scenario's table names — in instruction OR example) — that is overfitting and fails.\n\n**L2 STRUCTURE MISSING** — expressible today, but the artifact doesn't exist. Add it, inside the\nspace format (no core change): a new AGENT · a new TASKLIST or TASK NODE · a new SPACE FUNCTION · a\nnew capability grant or `canDelegateTo` edge on an existing agent.\n\n**L3 FRAMEWORK GAP** — today's primitives CANNOT express it, and you can point at where a lower rung\nwould go and show it has no way to say the thing. A core change (`sdk/org/libs/core|cli/**`), held to\nthe runtime discipline:\n- a new or improved FRONTMATTER FIELD on an agent / task, when no field says it; OR\n- a new GLOBAL + capability + DTS + injection + fork-intersection, when the model surface lacks the\n  power; OR\n- a change to the turn loop / fork / tasklist orchestrator / typecheck.\nShips LOCKSTEP (not-granted ⇒ not-injected ⇒ absent from the DTS ⇒ a clean typecheck error), WITH a\ntest that would have caught the gap, and the matching `org/docs/` page updated in the SAME change\n(`pnpm docs:check` is a hard gate). L3 is heavy and it is the judge's most dangerous power — enter it\nonly on proof, and flag it loudest of all in the report so the human reviewing knows a framework\nchange is in the diff.\n\n> The routing rebuild is the worked example that needs all three: THING misrouting where data lived\n> took L1 (the three-store triage rewrite), L2 (the `write_fact` / `retract_fact` / `reconcile_conflict`\n> / `answer_across_spaces` / `migrate_to_app_db` tasklists + DB grants), and